A 50-year-old woman has had a high fever over the past day. On physical examination she has papilledema. The gross appearance of her disease process is shown here. Which of the following laboratory test results is she most likely to have? <image 1> 

A. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 50 mm/hr
B. Serum lipase of 449 U/L
C. Total serum complement of 45 mg/dL
D. Serum carcinoembryonic antigen of 10 ng/mL
E. Serum alanine aminotransferase of 123 U/L
F. Proteinuria

The image shows the gross appearance of a brain with signs of inflammation and swelling, which is consistent with meningitis or encephalitis. Given the patient's symptoms of high fever and papilledema (swelling of the optic disc), the most likely diagnosis is meningitis.

Among the options provided, the erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) is a nonspecific marker of inflammation and can be elevated in various conditions, including infections like meningitis. Therefore, the most likely laboratory test result in this context is:

A. Erythrocyte sedimentation rate of 50 mm/hr
